about this dilemma is: Go away and read
and/or listen to <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">twenty million</NUMEX> words in your <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">L2</TIMEX> and
you will find that the problem is diminished.  The
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">counselor</ENAMEX>'s hope is that the <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">student</ENAMEX> will hone to
quasi-perfection a fine ability to detect, capture, and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">internalize</ENAMEX> information about the occurrence, co-occurrence
and patterning of lexis in context, plus a
lot else besides.  Maybe there was or is a subconscious
view that the path to L2 proficiency and success
is open only to those who can summon up the
intellectual energy and also physical, dictionary-(<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">man</ENAMEX>)handling
stamina for the task.  It is a moot
point whether it is better for the <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">student</ENAMEX> to read--
