wild <ENAMEX TYPE="ANIMAL">spinach</ENAMEX>, wild yam; or native <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">flax</ENAMEX>, nabox,
<ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">native cherry</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">native cranberry</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">native flax</ENAMEX>, native
<ENAMEX TYPE="PLANT">grass</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">native myrtle</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">native parsley</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">native</ENAMEX> plum;
or names in which the qualifier is a color, as in blue
<ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">gum</ENAMEX>, green wattle, white honeysuckle.  On the other
there were new names, borrowings from Aboriginal
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">languages</ENAMEX>, like boobook, dingo, koala, kurrajong,
