<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Dharuk</ENAMEX> (the <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Sydney</ENAMEX> language); descriptive names
like blackbutt, bottlebrush, duckbill, flooded <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">gum</ENAMEX>,
and gumtree; or popular adoptions of scientific
names like banksia, callistemon, casuarina, boronia,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">eucalyptus</ENAMEX>, and platypus.  In generic terms this is
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">manifested</ENAMEX> in the replacement of woods by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">bush</ENAMEX>,
once the inadequacy of woods is recognized, and by
the redefinition of words like forest and plain.  The
important contrast is between the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">bush</ENAMEX> vegetation
in its natural <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE_DESC">state</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE_DESC">country</ENAMEX> covered in such vegetation,
